<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="8d59e8e5-a3ae-5293-a0ec-3ed4d3ac23dd" activityNameId="7acd735d-0254-4d98-a303-e052024d1914" parentActivityId="0d72c259-8f37-4ddb-9a04-802d47ade444" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">calcium nitrate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Norge saltpeter</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The activity represents the production of calcium nitrate from limestone and nitric acid.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Calcium carbonate in limestone reacts with nitric acid given the formula:  CaCO3 + 2 HNO3 → Ca(NO3)2 + CO2 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The reaction yield is assumed to be 98.1%.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Calcium nitrate has an N-content of 17%. Non-reacting nitric acid and ammonia are considered to be recycled or re-used internally and not being liberated to the environment. This is due to the toxicity of reactants.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="04d83550-7c85-44f3-916b-424730a81963">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2012:Manufacture of fertilizers and nitrogen compounds</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process described here is the generic method used for the production of calcium nitrate from limestone and nitric acid.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Limestone (CaCO3) is usually neutralized in towers of circulating 40-48% nitric acid (HNO3). Acid solutions of calcium nitrate are fed again to the tower until the residual acidity of the solution decreases to 1,5-1,9% of HNO3. Then the free nitric acid is further neutralized with ammonia. Following the application of ammonia, some amount of ammonium nitrate forms, faciliating the crystallization of Ca(NO3)2 from a melt. The filtered solution containing ca. 49% of Ca(NO3)2 and 3% of NH4NO3 is evaporated under vacuum to 75-82% of Ca(NO3)2. This production method is used by most manufacturers of calcium nitrate in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS). </text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2010-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true"/>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
